{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"9bf35ee1-5cdb-46a9-a0ea-03aadda1478f","content":"With **MSTest.Sdk/3.8.0**, the migration is straightforward. In your project file, either:\n\n1. **Remove** the `<UseVSTest>true</UseVSTest>` property entirely (Microsoft.Testing.Platform is the default in MSTest SDK 3.4+), or\n2. **Set it to false**:\n   ```xml\n   <UseVSTest>false</UseVSTest>\n   ```\n\nThat's the only required change. A few things to be aware of:\n\n- **CLI differences** — you run tests with `dotnet test` as before, but the underlying runner changes. Some VSTest-specific command-line switches (e.g., `--logger`) are replaced by Microsoft.Testing.Platform equivalents (`--report-trx`).\n- **`.runsettings`** — still supported, but platform-specific configuration can also go in code via `[TestApplication]` entry point or builder APIs.\n- **Test Explorer in VS** — works with VS 17.10+ and the Microsoft.Testing.Platform. Older VS versions may need the compatibility layer (`Microsoft.Testing.Platform.MSBuild`), which MSTest.Sdk already includes.\n- **CI pipelines** — if you relied on `--logger trx`, switch to `--report-trx` or add the TRX report NuGet package.\n\nNo changes to your test source code are needed.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"96495322-22ab-4916-ab97-01dff7eeb42e","outputTokens":325,"requestId":"340A:6A01C:76EF646:8336BC4:69F3FAD9"},"id":"9180cf5e-471d-4b8e-bb5c-3fcc216ef307","timestamp":"2026-05-01T00:59:14.969Z","parentId":"69782747-940d-474c-94d9-5cad4e46b9bd"}
